    {\displaystyle x^{4}+1=(x^{4}-2x^{2}+1)+2x^{2}=(x^{2}-1)^{2}+\left(x{\sqrt {2}}\right)^{2}=\left(x^{2}+x{\sqrt {-2}}-1\right)\left(x^{2}-x{\sqrt {-2}}-1\right).}
  These factorizations work not only over the complex numbers, but also over any field, where either –1, 2 or –2 is a square. In a finite field, the product of two non-squares is a square; this implies that the polynomial 
  
    
      
        
          x
          
            4
          
        
        +
        1
        ,
      
    
    {\displaystyle x^{4}+1,}
   which is irreducible over the integers, is reducible modulo every prime number. For example,

  
    
      
        
          x
          
            4
          
        
        +
        1
        ≡
        (
        x
        +
        1
        
          )
          
            4
          
        
        
          
